<TITLE> PM seeks German help for power generation </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 17 (bdnews24.com)--Prime minister Sheikh Hasina has sought Germany's assistance in power generation by using solar energy and coal extraction, her press secretary said on Thursday. She sought the cooperation when newly appointed German ambassador Holger Michael met with her at her office, Abul Kalam Azad told reporters. During the meeting, the two discussed issues for strengthening relations between the two countries, further development of trade and commerce, and safeguarding human rights. Michael said Bangladesh and Germany were both affected by war and successfully got through the vulnerable condition. The prime minister thanked the German government for helping to re-establish democracy and development assistance to Bangladesh, Azad said. Hasina said her administration was firmly determined to build good governance, curb corruption and ensure transparency. The envoy lauded Hasina for her success in tackling crises after the government took over. Later, the prime minister handed a cheque of Tk 5 lakh to the wife of traffic sergeant Abdul Based who was run over and killed by a minibus at College Gate of Mohammadpur in Dhaka on May 19. She gave another cheque of Tk 1 lakh to the father of Akhter Hossain, a civilian who received bullet wounds outside the Peelkhana headquareters during the Feb 25-26 BDR mutiny. Milk Vita chairman Ahidullah Molla handed her a Tk 10 lakh cheque for the prime minister's relief fund. bd
